 guerrilla groups and autonomous movements, do not. Nevertheless what was at stake in all these ventures was the use of available means of expression in order to produce transformative effects, and they were all in different ways responding to ideas and practices of guerrilla struggle and specifically of guerrilla media. This book examines these radical media ecologies as guerrilla networks, emphasising the proximity and inseparability of radical media and political practices.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAlternative mass mediaxHistoryy20th century. 0aGuerrillasxHistoryy20th century. 0aNew LeftxHistoryy20th century. 0aRadicalism in mass mediaxHistoryy20th century. 0aTerrorism and mass mediaxHistoryy20th century. 4aFilm, Media, and Communication. 4aMedia Studies. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / Media & Internet .2bisacsh  aMedia Archaeology, Media Ecology, Radical Media, Guerrilla Media, Siegfried Zielinski, Red Army Fraction, Radio Alice, Italian Autonomia.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAUP eBook Package 2016-2018z978311066731808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060672008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz978311060425208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018z9783110603255oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Economics and Social Sciences 2018 Englishz978311060401608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2018z9783110603231oZDB-23-DSW40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048527533zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048527533423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/978904852